{
  "doc_id": "29429",
  "text": "Pectin can be obtained from many sources with a variation in the percentage yield. Commercial pectins are primarily extracted from citrus peels and apple pomace by dilute acid extraction. Sugar beet and sunflower head residues consist of 10 to 20% pectin [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Other pectin sources include cocoa husks, with about 9% pectin [CITATION_3] , beet and potato pulp and soy hull, with pectin contents about 26-28% [CITATION_4] . In previous experiments Slavov, Kyiohara and Yamada [CITATION_5] obtained water soluble pectins from waste rose petals and investigated their immunomodulating properties.",
